## Module 3: Recrystallization & Purification

### Purification Objective
Removal of contaminants and impurities to achieve forensic-grade purity.

### Standard Recrystallization Protocol Structure

#### Phase 1: Solvent Selection
**[STRICT]** Consider:
- Solubility at elevated temperature
- Solubility at reduced temperature
- Impurity solubility
- Boiling point
- Safety considerations

##### Common Solvent Systems
- Acetone/water mixtures
- Isopropanol
- Methanol
- Ethanol
- Mixed solvent systems

#### Phase 2: Dissolution
- Solvent volume calculation
- Heating method (water bath, hot plate)
- Temperature control
- Complete dissolution verification
- Hot filtration (if needed)

#### Phase 3: Crystallization
- Cooling rate control
  - Slow cooling (large crystals)
  - Rapid cooling (small crystals)
- Seeding procedures (if needed)
- Temperature profile
- Crystallization time

#### Phase 4: Isolation
- Filtration methods
- Washing protocols
- Drying conditions
- Yield determination

### Impurity Removal Protocols

#### Contaminant Types
**[STRICT]** Provide removal methods for:
- MSM (methylsulfonylmethane)
- Unreacted precursors
- Byproducts
- Catalyst residues
- Solvent residues

#### Specific Removal Methods
| Contaminant | Removal Method | Conditions |
|-------------|----------------|------------|
| MSM | Acetone wash | Cold acetone, filtration |
| Unreacted P2P | Acid-base extraction | pH manipulation |
| Iodine residues | Sodium thiosulfate wash | Aqueous solution |
| Metal residues | Chelation/filtration | EDTA treatment |

